I assume `nativeAudio.play()` is a `promise`. With your code you are not waiting to end the first method to call the second because the promise is not completed. You can do it chaining the promises or well with `async/await` way. 

Like: 

    async PlayList(){
     await this.nativeAudio.play(&#39;uniqueId1);
     await this.nativeAudio.play(&#39;uniqueId2);
     await this.nativeAudio.play(&#39;uniqueId3);
    }

Dynamically, I would do it like: 

    async PlayList(){
     const listIds = [&#39;uniqueId1&#39;, &#39;uniqueId2&#39;, &#39;uniqueId3&#39;];
     await Promise.all(listIds.map(async id =&gt; await this.nativeAudio.play(id));
    }

Hope it helps.

Was able to resolve through a help.

   

     playOne(track: string): Promise&lt;void&gt; {
      return new Promise(resolve =&gt; this.nativeAudio.play(track, resolve));
    }
    
    playAll(tracks: string[]): void {
      let player = (acc, track) =&gt; acc.then(() =&gt; this.playOne(track));
      tracks.reduce(player, Promise.resolve());
    }

Array.reduce allows us to feed the results of one iteration into the next. Each successive run waits on the last one and returns a new Promise on which the next will wait.

I hope it helps someone.

